   =20
      Pre-MBA
   =20
 =20
The way private equity hiring works is that big investment banks do the wor=
k of (1) screening college students, hiring the ones who seem best suited f=
or working long hours doing financial deals, and (2) teaching them how to b=
uild financial models=C2=A0and behave appropriately in meetings. Then the p=
rivate equity firms hire them from their banks. If you are a private equity=
 firm, you will want to hire people who have been through good two-year ana=
lyst programs at good banks, because they have been pre-screened and taught=
 things.But there is no particular reason to wait until they=E2=80=99re don=
e with the analyst program to=C2=A0interview=C2=A0them and give them (forwa=
rd-starting) job offers. You don=E2=80=99t have to ask them, like, =E2=80=
=9Cwhat did you learn about building LBO models during your time in the lev=
eraged finance group at Morgan Stanley?=E2=80=9D You can interview them hal=
fway through their time at the bank. You can interview them before they sta=
rt at the bank! Their job offer from the bank proves that the bank pre-scre=
ened them, and spending two years on the job=C2=A0ensures that they will be=
 taught the things bankers are ordinarily taught. Interview them before the=
y start at the bank, give them a job offer=C2=A0and say =E2=80=9Ccome back =
in two years when you=E2=80=99re done at the bank.=E2=80=9DThere are proble=
ms with this approach, but they are minor in the grand scheme of things, an=
d the big advantage is that the earlier you hire the more likely you are to=
 get first dibs on good candidates.=C2=A0And in fact private equity recruit=
ing can get=C2=A0arbitrarily close to hiring banking analysts before they s=
tart their banking jobs.=C2=A0The broader point is that there are lots of j=
obs for which the main qualifications are:=C2=A0=09Some other elite institu=
tion pre-screened you;=09That other institution provides some standardized =
training over a standardized period of time, say two years; and=09You seem =
personable in an interview.So here is a Wall Street Journal story about how=
=C2=A0=E2=80=9CSome M.B.A.s Are Getting Job Offers Before They Step Onto Ca=
mpus.=E2=80=9D If you are good enough to get into your business school, and=
 if you learn the normal things that people=C2=A0learn in business school, =
that=E2=80=99s all the employer needs to know; there=E2=80=99s no reason to=
 wait until you=E2=80=99ve actually taken classes to interview you:Just get=
ting accepted into business school is proving a career boost for some stude=
nts, who are fielding offers from consulting firms before their M.B.A. prog=
rams even begin.Major consulting firms including Bain & Co. and McKinsey & =
Co. say they are offering some 2023 internships to students who don=E2=80=
=99t start business school until this fall. Some offers come with the promi=
se of a full-time job after graduation in 2024.The early-bird recruiting ra=
ises the question: Why take on an expensive business-school degree when jus=
t getting accepted is enough to compel job offers?The offers, recruiters sa=
y, reflect the knowledge that companies expect students to acquire from M.B=
.A. programs that have a solid hiring record, and come after interviews, co=
aching and conversations about the candidates=E2=80=99 career goals.Also I =
enjoyed this claim:Some students say mixing with companies before school al=
lows them to focus on coursework and build relationships once the academic =
year starts.=C2=A0=E2=80=9CI wanted to get the getting-a-job portion of bus=
iness school out of the way so I could focus on my coursework,=E2=80=9D sur=
e.
