 This</a> really shows signs of being the next big banking scandal, and yet=
 it is so dumb:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">HSBC Holdings P=
lc fired a trader in London after scrutinizing the personal mobile phones o=
f some staff, in a sign of increased pressure on banks to closely monitor b=
usiness communications.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Earlier this =
year, the lender=E2=80=99s UK-based compliance team pushed some traders and=
 bankers to hand over their phones so they could examine business messages =
on platforms such as WhatsApp, according to people familiar with the matter=
. As result of the review a trader on the foreign exchange desk was dismiss=
ed, the people added, declining to identify the individual.=C2=A0</p><p sty=
le=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The bank=E2=80=99s review of the trader=E2=80=99s ph=
one found communications it deemed problematic, including a chat several ye=
ars ago with a broker who had bought the banker tickets for a sporting even=
t, the people said, asking not to be named discussing a private probe.=C2=
=A0</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Banks have tried to enhance surveillanc=
e on the fear that flexible working has exacerbated the use of unapproved c=
ommunications channels. Regulators have been pushing firms to make sure the=
ir employees don=E2=80=99t improperly use personal mobiles for conversation=
s with clients.</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">We talked abou=
t another one, at Credit Suisse Group AG, <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloo=
