</table><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The way private equity hiring works is=
 that big investment banks do the work of (1) screening college students, h=
iring the ones who seem best suited for working long hours doing financial =
deals, and (2) teaching them how to build financial models=C2=A0and behave =
appropriately in meetings. Then the private equity firms hire them from the=
ir banks. If you are a private equity firm, you will want to hire people wh=
o have been through good two-year analyst programs at good banks, because t=
hey have been pre-screened and taught things.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0=
;">But there is no particular reason to wait until they=E2=80=99re done wit=
h the analyst program to=C2=A0interview<em>=C2=A0</em>them and give them (f=
orward-starting) job offers. You don=E2=80=99t have to ask them, like, =E2=
=80=9Cwhat did you learn about building LBO models during your time in the =
leveraged finance group at Morgan Stanley?=E2=80=9D You can interview them =
halfway through their time at the bank. You can interview them before they =
start at the bank! Their job offer from the bank proves that the bank pre-s=
creened them, and spending two years on the job=C2=A0ensures that they will=
 be taught the things bankers are ordinarily taught. Interview them before =
they start at the bank, give them a job offer=C2=A0and say =E2=80=9Ccome ba=
ck in two years when you=E2=80=99re done at the bank.=E2=80=9D</p><p style=
=3D"margin: 16px 0;">There are problems with this approach, but they are mi=
nor in the grand scheme of things, and the big advantage is that the earlie=
r you hire the more likely you are to get first dibs on good candidates.=C2=
=A0And <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/28067458.26=
9601/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cubnl0aW1lcy5jb20vMjAxNC8wNy8wNi9idXNpbmVzcy93YWxsLXN0cm=
